,"30-35 years","36-39 years","40-44 years","45 years or older"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EWomen aged \u003Cstrong\u003E30-35 years\u003C/strong\u003E have the highest success rates with assisted reproductive technology, with cumulative live birth rates around 40-45% per complete treatment cycle. Women aged \u003Cstrong\u003E25-29 years\u003C/strong\u003E have slightly lower success rates, possibly due to fewer attempts per cycle. Success rates begin to decline in women aged \u003Cstrong\u003E36-39 years\u003C/strong\u003E and drop significantly in women aged \u003Cstrong\u003E40-44 years\u003C/strong\u003E due to decreased oocyte quality and quantity. Women aged \u003Cstrong\u003E45 years or older\u003C/strong\u003E have very low success rates (less than 5%) due to marked decline in both oocyte quality and quantity.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe decline in fertility with age primarily reflects deteriorating oocyte quality, with increased rates of chromosomal abnormalities in eggs from older women. Additionally, the total number of available oocytes (ovarian reserve) decreases with age, resulting in fewer eggs retrieved during stimulation cycles.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Live birth rates following in vitro fertilisation decrease significantly with advancing maternal age","Women aged 30-35 years have the highest success rates with assisted reproductive technology","Success rates drop dramatically after age 40 due to declining oocyte quality and quantity"],"references":["Rose BI. Approaches to oocyte retrieval for advanced reproductive technology cycles planning to utilize in vitro maturation: a review of the many choices to be made. J Assist Reprod Genet. 2014 Nov;31(11):1409-19. doi: 10.1007/s10815-014-0334-9. Epub 2014 Sep 12. PMID: 25212532; PMCID: PMC4389947.","Kumar P, Sait SF, Sharma A, Kumar M. Ovarian hyperstimulation syndrome. J Hum Reprod Sci. 2011 May;4(2):70-5. doi: 10.4103/0974-1208.86080. PMID: 22065820; PMCID: PMC3205536.","Wang J, Sauer MV. In vitro fertilization (IVF): a review of 3 decades of clinical innovation and technological advancement. Ther Clin Risk Manag. 2006 Dec;2(4):355-64. doi: 10.2147/tcrm.2006.2.4.355. PMID: 18360648; PMCID: PMC1936357","Choe J, Shanks AL. In Vitro Fertilization. [Updated 2023 Sep 4]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK562266/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"52730"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15754"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"52730","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/52730"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-04T15:07:26+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-04T15:08:01+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8445"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"67278"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":nul